'''Armenian Americans''' ({{lang-hy|<U+0531><U+0574><U+0565><U+0580><U+056B><U+056F><U+0561><U+0570><U+0561><U+0575><U+0565><U+0580>}}){{ref|name|a}} are [[Americans]] of [[Armenians|Armenian]] origin. They form the second largest community in the [[Armenian diaspora]] after [[Armenians in Russia]].<ref>{{cite news|title=WikiLeaks: U.S. Ambassadors <U+2018>Decipher<U+2019> Armenian American Diaspora|url=http://www.armenianweekly.com/2011/09/15/wikileaks-u-s-ambassadors-%E2%80%98decipher%E2%80%99-armenian-american-diaspora/|accessdate=31 January 2013|date=1 June 2004|author=[[Embassy of the United States, Yerevan]]|quote=Of the estimated 8-10 million people living outside the Republic of Armenia who consider themselves <U+201C>Armenians,<U+201D> the GOAM and major Armenian cultural and advocacy organizations estimate that 1.5-2 million live in the United States.  This number ranks second after the estimated 2 to 2.5 million Armenians that live most of the year in Russia or other CIS Countries.}}</ref> The first major wave of Armenian immigration to the US took place in late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, as Armenians fled the [[Hamidian massacres]] (1894<U+2013>1896) and [[Armenian Genocide]] (1915<U+2013>1923) that were taking place in the [[Ottoman Empire]]. Since the 1950s, Armenians from the Middle Eastern nations of [[Armenians in Turkey|Turkey]], [[Armenians in Iran|Iran]] and [[Armenians in Lebanon|Lebanon]] have migrated to America as a result of instability in those countries, and since the late 1980s, immigrants from [[Soviet Armenia]] could be found as well. Since the independence of [[Armenia]] from the Soviet Union in 1991 and the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War|following war]] with neighboring [[Azerbaijan]], additional Armenians fled to the US.

The Armenian American community is the most politically influential community of the [[Armenian diaspora]].<ref name="Von Voss"/> Organizations such as [[Armenian National Committee of America]] and [[Armenian Assembly of America]] advocate for the [[recognition of the Armenian Genocide]] by the US government and support stronger [[Armenia<U+2013>United States relations]].  The [[Armenian General Benevolent Union|Armenian General Benevolent Union (AGBU)]] is known for its financial support and promotion of Armenian cultural and [[List of Armenian schools in the United States|Armenian language schools]]. The [[Armenian language]] (both the [[Eastern Armenian|Eastern]] and mainly the [[Western Armenian|Western]] dialects) is spoken in the US, especially in California, where most recent Armenian immigrants and established Armenian communities have settled. The majority of Armenians are followers of the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]], the oldest national church in the world, and Armenian Americans are no exception. 

The 2011 [[American Community Survey]] estimated that 483,366 Americans held full or partial Armenian ancestry.<ref name="American Community Survey">{{cite web|title=Total ancestry categories tallied for people with one or more ancestry categories reported 2011 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|url=http://ia601608.us.archive.org/26/items/2011AmericanCommunitySurveyAncestry/2011Acs.pdf|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> Various organizations and media criticize these numbers as an underestimate, proposing 800,000 to 1,500,000 Armenian Americans instead. The highest concentration of Americans of Armenian descent is in the [[Greater Los Angeles area]], where 166,498 people have identified themselves as Armenian to the [[United States 2000 Census|2000 Census]], comprising over 40% of the 385,488 people who identified Armenian origins in the US at the time. [[Glendale, California]], a suburb of Los Angeles, is widely thought to be the center of Armenian American life.

==History==

===Early history ===
The first Armenians came to [[North America]] in the early 17th century. The first recorded Armenian in North America was Martin the Armenian, an [[Iran]]ian tobacco grower who settled in [[Jamestown, Virginia]] in 1618.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=33}}<ref name="Papazian"/> In 1653 and 1654, two Armenians from [[Istanbul|Constantinople]] were invited to [[Colony of Virginia|Virginia]] to raise [[Bombyx mori|silk worms]].{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=33}}<ref name="Papazian"/> A few other Armenians are recorded as having come to the US in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, but most came as individuals and did not establish communities. By the 1770s over 70 Armenians had settled in the colonies.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=33}} The persecution of Christian minorities under the Ottoman Empire and American missionary activities resulted in a small wave of Armenian migration to the US in 1830s from [[Cilicia]] and [[Western Armenia]]. [[Khachig Oskanian]], a Constantinople American missionary school student, arrived in America in 1834 to pursue higher education.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=33}} He later worked for the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' and became the [[New York Press Club]] president.<ref name="encyclopedia of ny"/> Many Armenians followed him and came to the US for education.<ref name="Armenian Printing">{{cite news|last=Matiossian|first=Vartan|title=Teotig: The First Historian of Armenian Printing|url=http://www.armenianweekly.com/2012/08/31/teotig/|newspaper=[[The Armenian Weekly]]|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=31 August 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Armenian-Americans-Boston-1908.jpg|thumb|250px|An Armenian family in [[Boston]], 1908]]

A number of Armenians were known to have served in the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union Army]] during the [[American Civil War]]. Three Armenian doctors&mdash;Simeon Minasian, Garabed Galstian, and Baronig Matevosian&mdash;worked at military hospitals in [[Philadelphia]].<ref name="Nersisyan">{{cite journal|last=Nersisyan|first=Mkrtich|title=<U+0554><U+0561><U+0572><U+0561><U+0584><U+0561><U+056F><U+0561><U+0576> <U+057A><U+0561><U+057F><U+0565><U+0580><U+0561><U+0566><U+0574><U+0568> <U+0531><U+0574><U+0565><U+0580><U+056B><U+056F><U+0561><U+0575><U+0578><U+0582><U+0574> <U+0570><U+0561><U+0575> <U+057A><U+0561><U+0580><U+0562><U+0565><U+0580><U+0561><U+056F><U+0561><U+0576> <U+0574><U+0561><U+0574><U+0578><U+0582><U+056C><U+056B> <U+056C><U+0578><U+0582><U+057D><U+0561><U+0562><U+0561><U+0576><U+0578><U+0582><U+0569><U+0575><U+0561><U+0574><U+0562>|journal=''[[Patma-Banasirakan Handes]]''|year=1961|volume=<U+2116> 2 (13)|pages=47<U+2013>66|trans_title=The American Civil War as Elucidated in the Armenian Periodical Press|publisher=[[Armenian National Academy of Sciences]]|language=Armenian}}</ref> The only Armenian known to have participated in hostilities was [[Khachadour Paul Garabedian]], who enlisted in the [[Union Navy]]. A naturalized citizen from [[Rodosto]], Garabedian served aboard the blockade ships ''[[USS Geranium (1863)|USS Geranium]]'' and ''[[USS Grand Gulf (1863)|USS Grand Gulf]]'' as a Third Assistant Engineer (and was later made an officer) from 1864 until his [[honorable discharge]] from the Navy in August 1865.<ref>{{cite web|last=Boltz|first=Martha M.|title=The Civil War's only Armenian soldier to be honored|url=http://communities.washingtontimes.com/neighborhood/civil-war/2011/sep/20/civil-wars-only-armenian-soldier-be-honored/|publisher=''[[The Washington Times]]''|accessdate=25 November 2012|date=20 September 2011}}</ref> 

In 1854, there were 20 Armenians in the United States, and by the 1870s their number reached 70.{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=59}} In the late 1870s, small Armenian communities existed in [[New York City]]; [[Providence, Rhode Island]]; and [[Worcester, Massachusetts]]. By the late 1880s, the number of Armenians in the US reached 1,500. Many of them were young male students of the American Evangelical Missions spread throughout the Ottoman Empire. About 40% came from the [[Vilayet of Mamuret-ul-Aziz|Province of Kharpert]].{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=33}} Before 1899, immigrants were not classified by ethnicity, but rather by country of birth, obscuring the ethnic origins of many Armenians.{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=63}} After 1869, however, Armenians from the eastern regions of the Ottoman Empire were registered as "Armenian" in American records. The number of Armenians that migrated to the US from 1820 to 1898 is estimated to be around 4,000.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=34}}

===First wave of immigration and the Interwar period===
Armenians began to arrive in the US in higher numbers than before in the late nineteenth century, most notably after the [[Hamidian Massacres]] of 1894<U+2013>1896, and before, during and after the [[Armenian Genocide]].{{sfn|Hovannisian|1997|p=390}} Before this mass migration to the US, the number of Armenians in the country was from 1,500 to 3,000, and mostly consisted of laborers.{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=71}}{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=13}}{{sfn|Avakian|1977|p=40}}

Over 12,000 Armenians from the Ottoman Empire came to the US throughout the 1890s.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=9}} With the exception of [[Fresno, California]], which had land suitable for farming, the earliest Armenian immigrants mostly settled in the northeastern industrial centers: New York City, Providence, Worcester, and [[Boston]].{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=13}} Armenian emigrants from the [[Russian Empire]] were only a minority in emigration from Armenian lands across the Atlantic (about 2,500 came in 1898<U+2013>1914), because Armenians were treated relatively better in Russia than in the Ottoman Empire.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=10}} Once in America, some Armenians organized [[political parties]] to serve various causes in America and in the homeland.<ref name="Armenian Printing"/> Turkish Armenian migration rose gradually in the first decade of the 20th century, as a result of the [[Young Turk Revolution]] of 1908, the [[Adana Massacre|Adana Massacre of 1909]], and the [[Balkan Wars]] in 1912<U+2013>1913.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=35}} Before the start of the [[World War I]], there were already 60,000 Armenians in the US.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=10}} As more Armenians fell victim to the genocide and more Armenians were deported, the Armenian American community grew gradually.

[[File:Worcester Armenian church.png|250px|left|thumb|Built in 1891, the [[Church of Our Savior, Worcester|Church of Our Savior]] in Worcester, Massachusetts was the first Armenian church in the US.<ref name="Blake">{{cite book|last=Blake|first=William D.|title=This day in Christian history|year=2011|publisher=Barbour Pub.|location=Ulrichsville, Ohio|isbn=978-1-60260-646-3|page=18}}</ref>]]

According to the American [[Immigration and Naturalization Service|Bureau of Immigration]], 54,057 Armenians entered the US between 1899 and 1917. The top listed countries of origin were [[Turkey]] (46,474), [[Russia]] (3,034), [[Canada]] (1,577), [[Great Britain]] (914) and [[Egypt]] (894). During this era, immigrants were asked to indicate which state that they were going to settle in; for Armenians, the most popular answers were [[New York]] (17,391), [[Massachusetts]] (14,192), [[Rhode Island]] (4,923), [[Illinois]] (3,313), [[California]] (2,564), [[New Jersey]] (2,115), [[Pennsylvania]] (2,002), [[Michigan]] (1,371).{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=67}} The largest Armenian American communities at that time were located in New York City, [[Fresno]], Worcester, Boston, Philadelphia, [[Chicago]], [[Jersey City]], [[Detroit]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Troy, New York|Troy]], and [[Cleveland]].{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=73}}

According to estimates, about 77,980 Armenians lived in the US in 1919.{{sfn|Malcom|1919|p=67}} An unprecedented number of Armenians entered the country in 1920,{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=10}} but the [[Immigration Act of 1924]] that restricted immigration from southern and eastern Europe barred many other Armenians from emigrating to the US.<ref name="Papazian"/> Most of the post-World War I immigrants were women and children, in contrast to the prewar immigration, which was predominantly young and male.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=10}} Like Italians, for whom this practice was known as ''campanilismo'', Armenian communities were often formed by people from the same village or town in the Ottoman Empire. It almost disappeared after [[World War II]].{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=184-185}}

[[Anti-Armenianism]] discrimination was widespread, and many Armenians struggled against overt discrimination and housing restrictions. The Armenians living in central California were often referred to by natives as "Fresno Indians" and "lower class Jews."{{sfn|Mirak|1983|p=399}} This first wave of immigration lasted until the mid-1920s, when the new immigration quotas were passed. This wave of immigrants established Armenian communities and organizations in the US, most notably the [[Armenian Apostolic Church]]. In the 1920s, Armenians began to move from rural regions to cities.

===Second wave of immigration===
[[File:Armenian dancers in downtown Manhattan, 1976.jpg|thumb|250px|Armenian American dancers in New York City in July 1976 during the [[United States Bicentennial]]]]

A new wave of Armenian immigrants came in the late 1940s, including [[Soviet Armenia]]n prisoners of war who were able to make their way westward after being freed from [[Nazi crimes against Soviet POWs|Nazi camps]]. The [[Displaced Persons Act of 1948]] allowed people displaced during the World War II to immigrate to the US.<ref name="Powell"/> From 1944 to 1952, 4,739 Armenians migrated to the US,{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=34}} many with the help of [[George Mardikian]]'s American National Committee to Aid Homeless Armenians (ANCHA).{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=37}}

However, the true second wave of immigration did not begin until the [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965]] abolished national origins quotas. After the passage of that act, Armenians from the [[Soviet Union]], [[Turkish Armenians|Turkey]], [[Lebanese Armenians|Lebanon]], [[Iranian Armenians|Iran]] and other Middle Eastern countries began migrating en masse to the US in the 1970s and 1980s, fleeing political instability in their host countries.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=37}} In the 1950s, most Armenian immigrants in the US were from Soviet Armenia and Turkey. The [[Istanbul riots]] in 1955 frightened the local Turkish Armenian population, which looked to the West for a safe and more prosperous life. 

The Armenians of USSR, on the other hand, were mostly survivors of the [[Armenian Genocide]] that never fully integrated into Soviet life after their repatriation in the 1940s. The large-scale emigration of Soviet Armenians, mainly to Western countries, began in 1956. About 30,000 Soviet Armenians entered the country from 1960 to 1984, and another 60,000 came throughout the late 1980s, during the [[Perestroika]] era.<ref name="Powell"/> The total number of Soviet Armenian emigrants from 1956 to 1989, over 80% of them to the US, is estimated at 77,000.<ref>{{cite book|last=M<U+00FC>nz|first=Rainer|title=Diasporas and ethnic migrants: German, Israel and post-Soviet successor states in comparative perspective|year=2003|publisher=Frank Cass|location=London|isbn=978-0-7146-5232-0|page=160}}</ref>

The 15-year-long [[Lebanese Civil War]] that started in 1975 and the [[Iranian revolution of 1979]] greatly contributed to the influx of Middle Eastern Armenians to the US.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=11}} The Armenian communities in these Middle Eastern countries were well established and integrated, but not assimilated, into local populations. Armenians in Lebanon and Iran are represented in the parliaments as ethnic minorities. Many lived in luxury in their former countries, and more easily handled multilingualism, while retaining aspects of traditional Armenian culture.<ref name="Papazian"/> This wave of newcomers revitalized the Armenian American community, especially in the Los Angeles area,{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=8-9}} where most second-wave Armenian immigrants settled.{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=101}} In 1970 about 65,000 Armenians resided in Southern California, and two decades later, in 1989, the number of Armenian Americans was estimated at 200,000.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=80}} Although the [[1980 US Census]] put the number of Armenians living in Los Angeles at 52,400, of which 71.9% were foreign born: 14.7% in Iran, 14.3% in the USSR, 11.5% in Lebanon, 9.7% in Turkey, 11.7% in other Middle Eastern countries (Egypt, [[Iraq]], [[Palestine]], etc.), and the rest in other parts of the world.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=16}}

