===Contemporary period ===
Immediately before and continuing into the time of the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], waves of Armenians from the [[Republic of Armenia]] and other former Soviet republics arrived for political reasons and economic opportunities, settling in older established Armenian communities across the country.<ref name="Papazian"/> The [[1988 Spitak earthquake]] and the [[dark and cold years|energy crisis in Armenia]] during the [[Nagorno-Karabakh War]] caused an estimated number of 700,000 Armenians to leave the country, most of whom ended up in Russia, still others in the US, and some in Europe.<ref>{{cite book|last=M<U+00FC>nz|first=Rainer|title=Diasporas and ethnic migrants: German, Israel and post-Soviet successor states in comparative perspective|year=2003|publisher=Frank Cass|location=London|isbn=978-0-7146-5232-0|page=161}}</ref> Annually, on average 2,000 people from Armenia migrated to the US since 1994, not including ethnic Armenians from Middle Eastern countries.<ref name="Powell">{{cite book|last=Powell|first=John|title=Encyclopedia of North American immigration|year=2005|publisher=Facts On File|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4381-1012-7|pages=17<U+2013>18}}</ref> According to the 2000 US Census, there were 65,280 Armenian-born people in the US: 57,482 in California, 1,981 in New York and 1,155 in Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Region and Country or Area of Birth of the Foreign-Born Population: 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://archive.is/mX1a}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Region and Country or Area of Birth of the Foreign-Born Population: 2000 by state|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://archive.is/mUMY}}</ref> According to the 2011 [[American Community Survey]], there were 85,150 Armenian-born people in the US, about 20,000 more than in 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Foreign-born population excluding population born at sea 2011 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://archive.is/dZM9}}</ref> According to the [[Embassy of the United States, Yerevan|US embassy in Yerevan]], about 21,000 citizens of the Republic of Armenia have moved to the US for permanent residency in the period from 1995 to 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gevorgyan|first=Siranuysh|title=Playing the Odds: End to US <U+2018>Green Card<U+2019> Lottery comes as disappointment for thousands of hopefuls in Armenia|url=http://www.armenianow.com/society/46921/armenia_united_states_green_card_diversity_lottery_end|accessdate=17 June 2013|date=14 June 2013|agency=[[ArmeniaNow]]}}</ref> Meanwhile, Armenian immigration from the Middle East continues, contributing to California's distinction of having by far the highest Armenian American population of any state.<ref name="Bedevian"/>

According to Dr. Anny Bakalian, Associate Director of the Middle East Center at the [[City University of New York]], "country of birth and childhood socialization, generation, and even cohort effect are important variables in understanding the behavior and attitudes of people of Armenian descent".{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=7}} The main subgroups of foreign-born Armenian Americans are ''Hayastantsis'' (Armenians from [[Armenia]]), ''Barskayes'' (Armenians from Iran) and ''Beirutsis'' (Armenians from Lebanon, mostly [[Beirut]]).<ref>{{cite book|last=Markowitz|first=Fran|title=Homecomings|year=2004|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham, Maryland|isbn=978-0-7391-0952-6|coauthors=Stefansson, Anders H.|page=122}}</ref>{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=26}} A 1990 [[University of California, Los Angeles]] study showed that by education and occupation, native-born and Iranian-born Armenians "tend to have the highest socioeconomic status... while those from Turkey have the lowest", although Turkish Armenians boast the highest rate of self-employment.{{sfn|Sabagh|Bozorgmehr|Der-Martirosian|1990|p=9}} In 1988, ''[[The New York Times]]'' article claimed that Middle Eastern Armenians prefer to settle in [[Glendale, California]], while Armenian immigrants from the Soviet Union were attracted to Hollywood, Los Angeles.<ref name="ny times 1988"/>

Armenians from Lebanon, where they had effectively established an active community, are more politicized,{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=186}} while the Armenians from Turkey are mostly connected with the Armenian Apostolic Church.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=185}} About 1/3 of all Turkish Armenians in America are self-employed.{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=102}} A group of Armenian Americans from Istanbul founded the [[Organization of Istanbul Armenians]] (OIA) in 1976,<ref>{{cite web|title=General Information|url=http://www.oia.net/history/|publisher=Organization of Istanbul Armenians|accessdate=12 December 2012}}</ref> which claimed over 1,000 members in Southern California as of 2011.<ref name="LA Times Istanbul Armenians">{{cite news|last=Esquivel|first=Paloma|title=A brotherhood is bolstered by food and friendship|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/sep/19/local/la-me-istanbul-armenian-20110919|accessdate=12 December 2012|date=19 September 2011|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> Iranian Armenians are known for fast integration into American society;<ref>{{cite book|last=Parks|first=Lisa|title=Planet TV: a global television reader|year=2003|publisher=New York University Press|location=New York|isbn=978-0-8147-6692-7|coauthors=Kumar, Shanti|page=395}}</ref> for example, only 31% of Armenian Americans born in Iran claim not to speak English well.{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=102}}

Armenian American criminal organizations have received widespread media attention, such as during the [[2010 Medicaid fraud]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nearly 100 charged, dozens arrested in operation targeting Armenian organized crime|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2011/02/nearly-100-arrested-charged-in-operation-targeting-armenian-organized-crime-.html|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=16 February 2011|accessdate=25 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Cracks Down on Armenian Crime Syndicate|first=Ian|last=Lovett|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/17/us/17armenian.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=16 February 2011|accessdate=25 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Manhattan U.S. Attorney Charges 44 Members and Associates of an Armenian-American Organized Crime Enterprise with $100 Million Medicare Fraud|url=http://www.fbi.gov/newyork/press-releases/2010/nyfo101310.htm|publisher=Federal Bureau of Investigation|accessdate=13 December 2012|date=13 October 2010}}</ref> However, in the city of [[Glendale, California]], where Armenians compose 27% of city's total population, only 17% of the crime in the city were perpetrated by Armenians in 2006.<ref name="Bedevian"/> A gang named [[Armenian Power]], composed of about 200 Armenian Americans, has operated in Los Angeles County since the late 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1357977/74-held-swoop-Armenian-Power-gang.html|title=Ruthless Armenian Power gang hit by 74 arrests in huge crackdown on organised crime|date=17 February 2011|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|accessdate=12 December 2012|quote=The group start as a street gang in East Hollywood, California, in the 1980s, identifying themselves with tattoos, graffiti and gang clothing... In all, the crime group is believed to have more than 200 members.}}</ref>

According to the [[2000 US Census]], there were 385,488 Americans of Armenian ancestry at that time.<ref name="2000 ancestry"/> The 2011 [[American Community Survey]] estimate found 483,366 Americans with full or partial Armenian ancestry.<ref name="American Community Survey"/> Higher estimates of 800,000 to 1,500,000 are offered by many Armenian and non-Armenian organizations, media and scholars. The German ethnographer Caroline Thon puts their number at 800,000,<ref name="Thon">{{cite book|last=Thon|first=Caroline|title=Armenians in Hamburg: an ethnographic exploration into the relationship between diaspora and success|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M<U+00FC>nster|location=Berlin|isbn=978-3-643-90226-9|page=25}}</ref> a number also offered by the ''[[Journal of Turkish Weekly]]''<ref name="turkish weekly">{{cite news|url=http://www.turkishweekly.net/article/11/armenian-diaspora-in-australia.html|title=Armenian Diaspora in Australia|last=Kasim|first=Kamer|newspaper=[[Journal of Turkish Weekly]]|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> and Dr. Harold Takooshian of [[Fordham University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dec17.org/armenian-americans.html|title=Armenian American's Immigration to California|last=Takooshian|first=Harold|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> Prof. Dennis R. Papazian of [[University of Michigan<U+2013>Dearborn]] claimed that there were 1,000,000 people of Armenian ancestry living in the US.<ref name="Papazian">{{cite journal|last=Papazian|first=Dennis|title=Armenians in America|journal=Journal of Eastern Christian Studies|url=http://www.umd.umich.edu/dept/armenian/papazian/america.html|volume=52|accessdate=25 November 2012|pages=311<U+2013>347|year=2000|issue=3-4|doi=10.2143/JECS.52.3.565605|publisher=University of Michigan-Dearborn}}</ref> ''[[Armenian Mirror-Spectator]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorspectator.com/2012/04/23/commentary-a-million-person-march-on-washington/|title=Commentary: A Million Person March on Washington|last=Azadian|first=Edmond Y.|date=23 April 2012|newspaper=[[Armenian Mirror-Spectator]]|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> 
the German news website ''[[Spiegel Online]]'' and ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'' reported the estimate of 1,200,000,<ref>{{cite news|last=Schmitz|first=Gregor Peter|title=Armenian Lobby's Triumph: Genocide Resolution Risks Shattering Relations with Turkey|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/world/armenian-lobby-s-triumph-genocide-resolution-risks-shattering-relations-with-turkey-a-511210.html|accessdate=5 December 2012|date=12 October 2007|newspaper=[[Spiegel Online]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2012/may/10/armenia-survives-caucasus/?pagination=false|title=Armenia Survives!|last=Judah|first=Tim|date=21 June 2012|publisher=''[[The New York Review of Books]]''|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> while the World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples, ''[[U.S. News & World Report]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usnews.com/news/world/articles/2007/10/18/an-ugly-truth|title=An Ugly Truth|last=Tolson|first=Jay|date=18 October 2007|newspaper=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jan/07/nation/na-armenia7/2|title=Genocide question hits home|last=Reynolds|first=Maura|date=7 January 2007|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> put the number at 1,400,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minorityrights.org/?lid=2614|title=Arab and other Middle Eastern Americans|publisher=World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples|accessdate=21 July 2012}}</ref> The [[Armenian National Committee of America]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anca.org/press_releases/press_releases.php?prid=1365|title=Barack Obama on the Importance of US-Armenia Relations|date=19 January 2008|publisher=[[Armenian National Committee of America]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Armenian Weekly]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.armenianweekly.com/2012/05/20/kim-kardashian-urges-support-for-telethon/|title=Kim Kardashian Urges Support for Telethon|date=20 May 2012|newspaper=[[The Armenian Weekly]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> ''[[The Armenian Reporter]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reporter.am/go/article/2011-02-11-armenian-lobby-faces-moment-of-truth|title=Armenian lobby faces moment of truth|last=Jemal|first=Timothy|date=11 February 2011|newspaper=[[The Armenian Reporter]]|accessdate=24 July 2012}}</ref> and [[Reuters]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Milliken|first=Mary|title=Armenian-American clout buys genocide breakthrough|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/10/12/us-usa-armenians-idUSN1144509820071012|accessdate=5 December 2012|date=12 October 2007|newspaper=[[Reuters]]}}</ref> offer the highest number, at around 1,500,000 Armenian Americans.

==Geographic distribution==
[[File:Armenians in Los Angeles County (2000).png|thumb|320px|Distribution of Armenians in the [[Los Angeles County]], 2000.]]

Most Armenian Americans are concentrated in major urban areas, especially in California and the [[Northeastern United States|Northeast]], and to a lesser extent in the [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]]. The highest concentrations of Americans of Armenian ancestry are in [[Greater Los Angeles Area|Los Angeles]], [[New York metropolitan area|New York]] and [[Greater Boston|Boston]]. According to the 2000 Census, the states with largest Armenian populations were [[California]] (204,631), [[Massachusetts]] (28,595), [[New York]] (24,460), [[New Jersey]] (17,094), [[Michigan]] (15,746), [[Florida]] (9,226), [[Pennsylvania]] (8,220), [[Illinois]] (7,958), [[Rhode Island]] (6,677) and [[Texas]] (4,941).<ref name="2000 ancestry"/>

===California===
The first Armenian arrived in California in 1874 and settled in Fresno.<ref>Nectar Davidian, ''The Seropians'' (Berkeley, 1965). p. iii; Bishop Mushegh Seropian [Serobian], ed., ''Amerikahay Taretsuytse 1912'' (American Armenian Almanac), vol. 1 (Boston: Kilikia Tparan, 1913), p. 56</ref> Fresno and the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] in general were the center of California Armenian community, but in the later decades, especially since 1960s, when significant number of Middle Eastern Armenians arrived in the US, Southern California attracted more and more Armenians.<ref name="Starr">{{cite book|last=Starr|first=Kevin|title=Coast of dreams: California on the edge, 1990<U+2013>2003|year=2006|publisher=Vintage Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-679-74072-8|page=175}}</ref>

Los Angeles and the surrounding area is, by far, the most crowded Armenian community in the US. It holds a little less than half of all Armenians living in the US, making it one of the [[Armenian population by urban areas|most populous Armenian communities outside of Armenia]]. The estimated numbers of Armenians of Southern California vary greatly: 250,000,<ref>Kouymjian, 2000 "... and particularly Los Angeles, which alone has nearly a quarter of a million Armenians in places like Hollywood, Glendale, and Pasadena."</ref> 350,000,<ref name="Starr"/> 400,000,<ref name="Thon"/> 450,000,<ref name="prolades">{{cite web|url=http://www.prolades.com/glama/la5co07/armenian_community.htm|title=The Armenian Community in the Los Angeles area|publisher=The Religion-In-The-Americas (RITA) Database|accessdate=20 July 2012}}</ref> 500,000,<ref name="Papazian"/> although the 2000 census reported 152,910 Armenians in [[Los Angeles County]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles County, California Ancestry: 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://ia601603.us.archive.org/14/items/LosAngelesCountyCaliforniaAncestry2000/117074325-Los-Angeles-County.pdf}}</ref> Just eleven years later, the 2011 American Community Survey one-year estimates put the number of Armenians in Los Angeles-Long Beach-Santa Ana area 214,618, about 29% growth from 2000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Los Angeles-Long Beach-SantaAna, CA Metro Area Total ancestry categories tallied for people with one or more ancestry categories reported 2011 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://ia601605.us.archive.org/13/items/LosAngeles-longBeach-santaanaCaMetroAreaAncestry2000/117073949-Aff-Reports.pdf}}</ref> The city of Los Angeles itself had an Armenian population of 64,997 in 2000.<ref name="ca cities 2000"/> Several districts of Los Angeles have high concentrations of Armenians, particularly in [[San Fernando Valley]]: [[North Hollywood]], [[Van Nuys, Los Angeles|Van Nuys]] and [[Encino, Los Angeles|Encino]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians in Van Nuys, Sherman Oaks, Encino, Tarzana, Studio City, North Hills, and Northridge|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/san-fernando-valley-ca/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> On October 6, 2000, a small community in [[East Hollywood]] was named [[Little Armenia, Los Angeles|Little Armenia]] by the [[Los Angeles City Council]]. The city council file on the adoption states that "the area contains a high concentration of Armenian businesses and residents and social and cultural institutions including schools, churches, social and athletic organizations."<ref>{{cite web|title=Council File: 00-1958 Title Little Armenia|url=http://cityclerk.lacity.org/lacityclerkconnect/index.cfm?fa=ccfi.viewrecord&cfnumber=00-1958|publisher=City of Los Angeles Office of the City Clerk|accessdate=7 December 2012}}</ref> 

[[File:Glendale panorama.jpg|thumb|left|300px|[[Glendale, California]] has the highest concentration of Armenians in the nation and the highest outside of Armenia.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grudin|first=Nicholas|title=Armenian population up Valley, Glendale and Burbank show big percentage hikes|url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/ARMENIAN+POPULATION+UP+VALLEY,+GLENDALE+AND+BURBANK+SHOW+BIG...-a091245026|accessdate=19 December 2012|date=8 September 2002|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]}}</ref>]]

Glendale, just a few miles away from [[downtown Los Angeles]], has a population of about 200,000, of which, according to some estimates, 40% is Armenian.<ref>{{cite news|last=Covarrubias|first=Amanda|title=New Era for Glendale Armenians|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/aug/08/local/me-armenian8|accessdate=19 October 2012|date=8 August 2005|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Milliken|first=Mary|title=Armenian-American clout buys genocide breakthrough|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2007/10/12/us-usa-armenians-idUSN1144509820071012|accessdate=11 December 2012|date=12 October 2007|agency=[[Reuters]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians in Glendale, CA|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/glendale-ca/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=19 October 2012}}</ref> According to the 2000 Census 53,840 people or 27% of the population identified themselves Armenian in Glendale.<ref name="ca cities 2000"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Armenian Ancestry|url=http://www.epodunk.com/ancestry/Armenian.html|publisher=[[ePodunk]]|accessdate=25 November 2012|date=October 2005}}</ref> Glendale also home to the highest percentage of people born in Armenia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Top 101 cities with the most residents born in Armenia (population 500+)|url=http://www.city-data.com/top2/h102.html|publisher=City-Data.com|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref> Other than Glendale and Los Angeles proper, significant Armenian populations reside in [[Burbank, California|Burbank]] (8,312), [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] (4,400), [[Montebello, California|Montebello]] (2,736), [[Altadena, California|Altadena]] (2,134), [[La Crescenta-Montrose, California|La Crescenta-Montrose]] (1,382).<ref name="ca cities 2000">{{cite web|title=Ancestry: 2000 All places within California|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://ia601608.us.archive.org/12/items/AllPlacesInCaliforniaAncestry2000/AllPlacesWithinCaliforniaAncestry2000.pdf}}</ref> The [[Armenian Genocide Martyrs Monument]], the oldest and largest Armenian Genocide memorial in the US, is located in Montebello.

Dr. Seta Kazandjian described the current situation in her 2006 book as following: 
{{cquote|Waves of immigration into the Los Angeles area have resulted in the formation of strong communities in neighborhoods and citites such as Hollywood, Glendale. and North Hollywood. In these neighborhoods, an Armenian can live a very active social and occupational life and receive many services without speaking a word of English and interacting only with Armenians. Armenian-speaking food vendors, pharmacists, physicians, dentists, lawyers, tailors, hair stylists, shop owners and mechanics are all available. Up to three different 24-hour Armenian language television and radio channels are available. There are various social activities to attend for the Armenian community every day. Therefore, individuals exist who are not acculturated at all to the dominant American culture, as well as those who have chosen to separate from the Armenian community and acculturate completely, and many who are in the middle of acculturation spectrum.<ref>{{cite book|last=Kazandjian|first=Seta|title=The Effects of Bilingualism and Acculturation on Neuropsychological Test Performance: A Study with Armenian Americans|year=2006|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-542-84512-3|pages=27<U+2013>28}}</ref>}}

;Fresno
Fresno, California was the first major Armenian community in the Western US. It was a major destination for early Armenian immigrants from the Ottoman Armenia, many of whom were engaged in agriculture. Armenians were the largest minority group in Fresno County. The city is also widely known as the birthplace of [[William Saroyan]], many of whose stories are set there.<ref name="fresno community">{{cite web|title=Armenians in Fresno, CA|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/fresno-ca/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> Today, an estimated number of about 40,000 Armenian live in Fresno.<ref name="ny times 1988">{{cite news|last=Reinhold|first=Robert|title=Echoes From Armenia In Southern California|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1988/03/21/us/echoes-from-armenia-in-southern-california.html|accessdate=3 December 2012|date=21 March 1988|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> According to the 2000 Census 9,884 Armenians lived in [[Fresno County]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ancestry 2000: Fresno County, California|url=http://ia601603.us.archive.org/30/items/FresnoCountyCaliforniaAncestry2000/FresnoCountyCaliforniaAncestry2000.pdf|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=20 December 2012}}</ref> The area around the [[Holy Trinity Church, Fresno|Holy Trinity Church]] is called [[Old Armenian Town, Fresno, California|Old Armenian Town]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Old Armenian Town: A living culture|url=http://discovercentralvalley.com/frs_church.htm|publisher=''[[The Fresno Bee]]''|accessdate=16 December 2012}}</ref> 

;San Francisco Bay Area
The Northern Californian Armenian population isn't as populous as the Southern portion of the state. Armenians are mostly concentrated in and around the cities of [[San Francisco]], [[San Jose, California|San Jose]] and [[Oakland]]. The 2000 Census reported only 2,528 Armenians in the San Francisco, but it probably underestimated the actual number.<ref name="san francisco">{{cite web|title=Armenians in the San Francisco Bay Area|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/sf-bay-area-ca/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=44}}

===Northeast===
;New York
Since the 19th century the first Armenians appeared to New York. The states of New York and Massachusetts were top destinations for Armenian immigrants in early twentieth century. The area between the East 20th St., [[Lexington Avenue]] and the Third Avenue, where a compact Armenian population lived and Armenian shops existed, was called "Little Armenia until the 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Saturday Review|year=1957|volume=40|author=Bernard Augustine De Voto|page=16|publisher=Saturday Review Associates}}</ref> The area was mentioned in 1914 book ''Our Mr. Wren: The Romantic Adventures of a Gentle Man'' by [[Sinclair Lewis]] (the 1930 [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Noble Prize Winner]]).<ref name="new york community">{{cite web|title=Armenians in New York, NY|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/new-york-ny/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> Today, according to estimates there are 150,000 Armenians in the Tri-State area. [[Queens]] is home to some 50,000 Armenian Americans, [[Manhattan]] has 10,000 Armenian population.<ref name="NY AGBU">{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20071121071951/http://agbu.org/publications/article.asp?A_ID=65|title=Tracking Armenians in New York|last1=Vartanian|first1=Hrag|date=1 April 2002|publisher=[[Armenian General Benevolent Union]]|accessdate=21 July 2012|quote=Today, Manhattan's community has shrunk to 10,000 of the 150,000 Armenians in the Greater New York area. As the most culturally diverse county in the nation, Queens was and perhaps still is home to the bulk of Tri-State Armenians with today's population hovering around 50,000. }}</ref>

[[File:Armenian Heritage Park.jpg|thumb|250px|The [[Armenian Heritage Park]] in downtown [[Boston]] ]]

;Boston
Stepan Zadori, an [[Armenians in Hungary|Hungarian Armenian]], is the first known Armenian to came to Boston, The Armenian community in Boston wasn't founded until 1880s.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=41}} Today, estimates say that Armenians number from 50,000 to 70,000 in the Greater Boston area.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=41}}<ref>{{cite web|title=About us|url=http://www.armenianradioboston.com/about.html|publisher=Armenian Independent Broadcasting of Boston|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref> The [[Armenian Heritage Park]], dedicated to the victims of the Armenian Genocide, was opened in downtown Boston on May 22, 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mass. Gov. to dedicate Armenian Heritage Park|url= http://articles.boston.com/2012-05-22/news/31815449_1_dedication-ceremony-local-immigrant-community-massachusetts-gov|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=22 May 2012|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> [[Watertown, Massachusetts]] is the center of Boston Armenians, where according to estimates about 7,000 to 8,000 people of Armenian origin reside,<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians in Watertown, MA|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/watertown-ma/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=10 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=O'Brien|first=Keith|title=ADL local leader fired on Armenian issue|url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/massachusetts/articles/2007/08/18/adl_local_leader_fired_on_armenian_issue/|accessdate=10 December 2012|date=18 August 2007|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]}}</ref> though the 2000 Census put the number only at 2,708.<ref name="2000 census mass">{{cite web|title=Ancestry: 2000 All places within Massachusetts|url=http://ia601508.us.archive.org/21/items/AllPlacesInMassachusettsAncestry2000_459/mass.pdf|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> The [[Armenian Library and Museum of America]] is located in Watertown. Other towns in the area with significant Armenian populations are Worcester (1,306), [[Belmont, Massachusetts|Belmont]] (1,165), [[Waltham, Massachusetts|Waltham]] (1,091) and the city of Boston (1,080).<ref name="2000 census mass"/> 

Other major northeastern cities with significant Armenian populations include Providence and Philadelphia. Like other Armenian communities in America, Armenian communities in these cities have it roots in late 19th century and early 20th century. Currently, Philadelphia holds about 15,000 Armenian American population{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=45}} and over 7,000 live in Providence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians in Providence, RI|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/providence-ri/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref>{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=45}}

===Other communities===
Other sizable Armenian American communities exist in the [[Midwest]] and in the [[Southern United States|South]], but in much smaller numbers than the Northeastern states and California.

The early Armenian immigrants in Detroit were mostly laborers. In later decades, particularly since 1960s Middle Eastern Armenians immigrated to Michigan. The Armenian community has been described as "highly educated, professional and prospering."<ref name="detroit">{{cite web|title=Armenians in the Metropolitan Detroit Area|url=http://www.umd.umich.edu/dept/armenian/papazian/detroit.html|work=Ethnic Groups in Michigan, Vol. 2 of The Peoples of Michigan|publisher=The Ethnos Press|accessdate=18 December 2012|author=Dennis Papazian, Carolyn Sirian|location=Detroit|pages=12<U+2013>17|year=1983}}</ref> Today, they number about 22,000.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=41}} Chicago's Armenians also first settled in the city in late 19th century in small numbers, but it increased through the 20th century,<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenians in Chicago, IL|url=http://www.hayk.net/destinations/chicago-il/|publisher=''Hayk the Ubiquitous Armenian''|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> reaching about 25,000 by today.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=44}} As of 2003 more than 8,000 Armenian Americans lived in [[Washington, DC]].{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=40}} The [[Armenian Genocide Museum of America]] is to be located in the capital. In the turn of the century, there is a tend of gradual increase in number of Armenians living outside of traditional settlement areas. For instance, the number of Armenians in skyrocketed in the states of [[Nevada]] (from 2,880 in 2000 to 5,845 in 2010), Florida (9,226 to 15,856) and Texas (4,941 to 14,459).<ref name="2010 acs by states">{{cite web|title=Total ancestry categories tallied for people with one or more ancestry categories reported by states 2010 American Community Survey 1-Year Estimates|url=http://ia601601.us.archive.org/24/items/AncestryIn2010ByStates/2010States.pdf|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref>

==Culture==
[[File:Multilingual road sign in Glendale, CA.jpg|thumb|225px|A road sign in Glendale, California in Spanish, English and Armenian]]

===Language===
Armenian Americans are one of the least assimilated [[White American|White ethnic groups in the US]]. Today, more than half of the Armenians living in the US speak the [[Armenian language]]. For comparison, only about 6% of [[Italian American]]s, 32% of [[Greek American]]s and 70% of [[Albanian American]]s speak their native language .<ref name="2000 ancestry">{{cite web|title=Ancestry: 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=17 December 2012|url=http://ia801601.us.archive.org/29/items/Ancestry2000/Ancestry2000.pdf}}</ref><ref name="2000 languages"/> The main reason for this is the fact that a significant part of Armenian Americans are foreign-born or are first-generation Americans and there are tens of Armenian-language schools in America.

The Armenian language has two distinct standardized forms: [[Western Armenian]] and [[Eastern Armenian]], both widely spoken among the Armenian American community. The main differences between them are mostly in pronunciation and in the formation of verbs.<ref name="American Midwest">{{cite book|last=Sisson|first=Richard|title=The American Midwest: an interpretive encyclopedia|year=2006|publisher=Indiana Univ. Press|location=Bloomington, Indiana|isbn=978-0-253-34886-9|page=320}}</ref> Armenians from [[Armenians in Lebanon|Lebanon]], [[Armenians in Turkey|Turkey]], [[Armenians in Syria|Syria]] and few other countries speak the Western dialect, which was spoken in so-called [[Western Armenia]], the eastern regions of Turkey with historical Armenian presence. In early 20th century the Turkish Armenian population was targeted a mass killing by the Turkish government, known as the [[Armenian Genocide]]. The population was deported to the Syrian desert, where many died, others fled to foreign countries and established communities. Lebanon and Syria had the largest Armenian communities prior to the Second World War, after which many left for Soviet Armenia or migrated to Europe and Americas. Eastern Armenian is primarily spoken in the Republic of Armenia and Iran, though the Iranian Armenians have their dialect.<ref>{{cite book|last=Khanam|first=R.|title=Encyclopaedic ethnography of Middle-East and Central Asia|year=2005|publisher=Global Vision|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-8220-062-3|page=54}}</ref> Also, Western and Eastern Armenian use two different spellings. The Armenians in Armenia use the [[Armenian orthography reform of 1922<U+2013>1924|reformed orthography]], while Armenians of the most [[Armenian diaspora|diaspora]] countries (including Lebanon, Syria, Turkey and Iran) use the [[Traditional Armenian orthography|traditional orthography]].{{sfn|Adalian|2010|pp=397-398}}

Between 1910 and 1970, the language of only foreign-born population in the United States was taken into account. In 1910, the number of Armenian speakers in the US was 23,938. It grew up to 37,647 in 1920, 51,741 in 1930, 40,000 in 1940, 37,270 in 1960 and 38,323 in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0029/tab06.html|title=Mother Tongue of the Foreign-Born Population: 1910 to 1940, 1960, and 1970|date=9 March 1999|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012}}</ref> According to the [[1980 US Census]] 100,634 people in the nation spoke Armenian, 69,995 of them were foreign-born.<ref name="1980, 1990, 2000 language">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/hhes/socdemo/language/data/acs/Table2.xls|title=Languages Spoken at Home: 1980, 1990, 2000, and 2007|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=6 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="census1980-90"/> The [[1990 US Census]] revealed 308,096 people of Armenian ancestry at the time and 149,694 people who indicated Armenian as their native language. Majority of Armenian-speakers (115,017) were foreign-born.<ref name="census1980-90">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/population/www/documentation/twps0029/tab05.html|title=Language Spoken at Home for the Foreign-Born Population 5 Years and Over: 1980 and 1990|date=9 March 1999|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=18 Deccmber 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/hhes/socdemo/language/data/census/table5.txt|title=Detailed Language Spoken at Home and Ability to Speak English for Persons 5 Years and Over --50 Languages with Greatest Number of Speakers: United States  1990|year=1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>

According to the [[2000 US Census]] there were 385,488 ethnic Armenians living in the US, and 202,708 people identified Armenian as [[Language Spoken at Home (U.S. Census)|'Language Spoken at Home']]. The overwhelming majority of Armenian-speakers lived in California (155,237). Other states with significant number of Armenian-speakers were New York (8,575) and Massachusetts (8,091).<ref name="2000 ancestry"/><ref name="2000 languages">{{cite web|url=http://www.census.gov/population/cen2000/phc-t20/tab05.pdf|title=Detailed List of Languages Spoken at Home for the Population 5 Years and Over by State: 2000|date=25 February 2003|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=18 August 2012}}</ref> About 2/3 of Armenians speakers call Los Angeles County home.<ref name="Bedevian">{{cite book|last=Bedevian|first=Harry Sahag|title=Student, Staff, and Parent Perceptions of the Reasons for Ethnic Conflict Between Armenian and Latino Students|year=2008|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-60688-8|pages=5<U+2013>6}}</ref> The 2011 American Community Survey 3-year estimates put the number of Armenian-speakers at 240,095. According to the same source 130,735 of them knew English "very well" and 109,360 knew English less than "very well".<ref>{{cite web|title=Language spoken at Home by ability to speak English for the population 5 years and over 2009<U+2013>2011 American Community Survey 3-Year Estimates|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=22 December 2012|url=http://archive.is/5SDU}}</ref> 

A 2007 study showed that 16% of Armenians born in Lebanon, 29% in Armenia (including Soviet Armenia), 31% in Iran and 36% in Turkey are not proficient in English.{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=102}} Many foreign-born Armenians are multilingual, speaking at least one language other than Armenian and English. For instance, Armenians from Armenia might know [[Russian language|Russian]], Armenians from Lebanon, Syria may know [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and French, almost all Iranian Armenians speak [[Persian language|Persian]] and Istanbul Armenians speak [[Turkish language|Turkish]].<ref name="Papazian"/><ref name="LA Times Istanbul Armenians"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Naficy|first=Hamid|title=The making of exile cultures Iranian television in Los Angeles|year=1993|publisher=University of Minnesota Press|location=Minneapolis|isbn=978-0-8166-2084-5|pages=86<U+2013>87}}</ref> 

[[File:Rose and Alex Pilibos Armenian school.jpg|thumb|325px|[[Rose and Alex Pilibos Armenian School]] in [[Little Armenia, Los Angeles|Little Armenia]] neighborhood of [[East Hollywood, Los Angeles|East Hollywood]] is the largest Armenian school in the US with more than 1,000 students.]]

===Education===
{{see also|List of Armenian schools in the United States}}
Early Armenian immigrants were one of the most literate ethnic groups to enter the US with 76% literacy. In comparison, only 46% of southern Italians, 74% of Eastern European Jews and 99% of Finns were literate.<ref name="American Midwest"/> Today, 41% of American-born Armenians have at least a 4 year college degree. The rate is lower for foreign-born Armenians.{{sfn|Samkian|2007|p=102}}

The first Armenian [[Sunday school]] in the US was founded in late 1880s in New York by Barsegh Vardukyan.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=51}} Since the 1960s many Armenian bilingual schools have been established in communities throughout the country. [[Ferrahian Armenian School]], founded in 1964, is the oldest Armenian daily school in America.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=51}} Besides this, there are over one hundred Armenian schools that operate on weekends only.<ref name="Papazian"/> Mashdots College in [[Glendale, California]], founded in 1992, is the only Armenian higher education institution in the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Moskowitz|first=Gary|title='Only the beginning'|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2004-06-21/news/export9477_1_graduate-computer-technician-students|accessdate=4 February 2013|date=21 June 2004|agency=''Glendale News-PressTerms''|quote=Mashdots College, which opened in 1992 in Glendale, is the only  four-year Armenian institution of higher education in the United States.}}</ref>

===Religion===
{{See also|List of Armenian churches in the United States}}
Most Armenian Americans are adherents of the Armenian Apostolic Church, the largest [[Oriental Orthodox]] church in the US.<ref name="Laderman">{{cite book|last=Laderman|first=Gary|title=Religion and American cultures|year=2003|publisher=ABC- CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=978-1-57607-238-7|page=302}}</ref> It possess over 90 churches throughout the nation.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=38}} It was reported that 80% of Armenian Americans are Armenian Apostolic, 10% are Protestant (mostly [[Armenian Evangelical]]) and 3% are [[Armenian Catholic Church|Armenian Catholic]].<ref name="encyclopedia of ny">{{cite book|title=The encyclopedia of New York State|year=2005|publisher=Syracuse University Press|location=Syracuse, NY|isbn=978-0-8156-0808-0|author=Eisenstadt, Peter R.; Moss, Laura-Eve|page=118}}</ref> 

The Armenian Apostolic Church is the oldest national church in the world, had major role in protecting the Armenian identity through the centuries of foreign domination.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=46}} Many Armenian communities in the country are concentrated around churches that serve as community centers. The first Armenian Apostolic church in America named [[Church of Our Savior, Worcester|Church of Our Savior]] was built in 1891 in Worcester.<ref name="Laderman"/> The American Diocese of the Church was established in 1898 by Catholicos [[Mkrtich Khrimian]].<ref name="Blake"/> In 1916 there were 34 Armenian parishes with 27,450 members with predominantly male population. Top states with Armenian church followers lived in Massachusetts, Michigan, California and New York.<ref>{{cite web|title=The first Armenian Orthodox churches in America|url=http://orthodoxhistory.org/2011/01/25/the-first-armenian-orthodox-churches-in-america/|publisher=The Society for Orthodox Christian History in the Americas|accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> The Western Diocese was established in 1927.<ref name="churches yearbook"/>

[[File:St. Vartan Armenian Cathedral.jpg|thumb|250px|[[St. Vartan Cathedral]] in downtown Manhattan]]

After the Soviets took over the power in Armenia in 1920, the Armenian American community was divided into two camps: one supporting Soviet Armenia (mostly members of the [[Social Democrat Hunchakian Party|Hunchak]] and [[Armenian Democratic Liberal Party|Ramgavar]] parties), another one against it (mostly made up of [[Armenian Revolutionary Federation|ARF]] members). During the [[Century of Progress|1933 World's Fair]], [[Leon Tourian]], the primate of the Eastern Diocese of the Armenian Apostolic Church of America, refused to give a speech, because the [[Flag of Armenia|Armenian tricolor]] of the [[Democratic Republic of Armenia|1918-1920 Republic]] was hang behind him, while [[Etchmiadzin]], the seat of the [[Catholicos of All Armenians]], was in Armenia that was then part of the Soviet Union and used a different flag. This upset the Dashnak members present in the ceremony. The conflict reached a crisis on December 24, 1933, when several members of ARF assassinated Archbishop Tourian during the Christmas Eve service in New York's [[Holy Cross Armenian Apostolic Church (New York City)|Holy Cross Armenian Apostolic Church]].<ref name="Laderman"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Arax|first=Mark|title=In my father's name: a family, a town, a murder|year=1997|publisher=Pocket Books|location=New York|isbn=978-0-671-01002-7|pages=31<U+2013>32|edition=August 1997.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Alexander|first=Ben|url=http://www.historycooperative.org/journals/jaeh/27.1/alexander.html|title=Contested Memories, Divided Diaspora: Armenian Americans, the Thousand-day Republic, and the Polarized Response to an Archbishop's Murder|journal=Journal of American Ethnic History|volume=27|issue=1|year=2007}}</ref>{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=47}}

On October 12, 1957, during the peak of the [[Cold War]], a number of parishes of the Armenian Apostolic Church in America, which were unaffiliated since 1933, came together under the [[Holy See of Cilicia]] with the headquarters in Lebanon, close to the Armenian Revolutionary Federation.<ref name="Laderman"/><ref name="churches yearbook">{{cite book|title=Yearbook of American & Canadian Churches 2012|year=2012|publisher=Abingdon Press|isbn=978-1-4267-5610-8|author=National Council of Ch of Christ in USA|chapter=[http://books.google.com/books?id=5DWeLz28b88C&pg=PT136&dq=Western+Diocese+of+the+Armenian+Church+of+America%5B&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ZJjDUKWFJMLJ0QGNuoG4BQ&ved=0CD8Q6AEwBQ Armenian Apostolic Church of America]}}</ref><ref name="Kouymjian">{{cite web|last=Kouymjian|first=Dickran|authorlink=Dickran Kouymjian|title=Armenians in the United States|url=http://armenianstudies.csufresno.edu/faculty/kouymjian/articles/us_armenians.htm|publisher=California State University, Fresno|accessdate=7 December 2012|date=December 1992}}</ref> After the World War II, Archbishop [[Tiran Nersoyan]] led the church through a second founding, which saw the framing of by-laws to govern the diocese; the creation of a nation-wide youth organization; the initiation of a project to build an Armenian cathedral in [[Manhattan]]; and the entry of the Armenian Church into the ecumenical movement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hower|first=Marvie|title=Tiran Nersoyan, An Archbishop, Scholar and Author, Is Dead at 85|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1989/09/03/obituaries/tiran-nersoyan-an-archbishop-scholar-and-author-is-dead-at-85.html|accessdate=29 December 2012|date=3 September 1989|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The middle 1950s saw an uptick in immigration and a building boom of Armenian churches, with new communities proliferating across the US. A generation of leaders born in America also began to exert itself. The first American-born Armenian priest was ordained in 1956. In 1961, St. Nersess Armenian Seminary was established in Illinois (later, it would move to New York). A spirit of renewed vigor was embodied by Archbishop [[Torkom Manoogian]], who governed the diocese as primate from 1966 to 1990.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vitello|first=Paul|title=Torkom Manoogian, Archbishop of Armenian Orthodox Church, Dies at 93|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/19/nyregion/torkom-manoogian-archbishop-of-armenian-orthodox-church-dies-at-93.html?_r=0|accessdate=30 December 2012|date=19 October 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The period saw a large influx of Armenian immigrants. These developments refocused the priorities of the Armenian Church in America. The need for humanitarian relief to the Armenian homeland, as well as outreach to [[refugee]]s settling throughout the US (concentrated in New York and Los Angeles), led to the creation of the [[Fund for Armenian Relief]]<U+2014>through which the church delivers material and medical aid to Armenia.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=46}}

Today, more than 120 Armenian parish communities exist on the continent, with two-thirds operating as fully organized churches with sanctuaries. Archbishop [[Khajag Barsamian]] is primate of the Eastern Diocese (since 1990); Archbishop [[Hovnan Derderian]] of the Western Diocese (since 2003). The dioceses maintain strong connections to the [[Mother See of Holy Etchmiadzin]], and the current Supreme Patriarch, His Holiness [[Karekin II]], the 132nd Catholicos of All Armenians.

[[Armenian Evangelical Church|Armenian Evangelical]] form the second largest denomination among Armenian Americans, with 1 out of 10 being a follower.<ref name="encyclopedia of ny"/> As of 1993 there were 28 Armenian Protestant Churches.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=93}} A small number of Armenian Americans are followers of the Armenian Catholic Church. Their number is estimated to be around 25,000.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pope Names New Eparch for Armenian Catholics In US And Canada|url=http://old.usccb.org/comm/archives/2011/11-107E.shtml|publisher=United States Conference of Catholic Bishops|accessdate=8 December 2012|date=21 May 2011}}</ref> In 1990 there were 6 Armenian Catholic Churches in the United States.{{sfn|Bakalian|1993|p=93}}

===Media===
The first Armenian-language newspaper in the US, named ''Aregak'' (<U+0531><U+0580><U+0565><U+0563><U+0561><U+056F>, "Sun"), was published in [[Jersey City]] in 1888. Over 300 newspapers have been published since then.<ref name="Armenian Printing"/>{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=77}} Today, numerous Armenian newspapers (both in Armenian and English) are published throughout the country. ''[[Asbarez]]'' (<U+0531><U+057D><U+057A><U+0561><U+0580><U+0567><U+0566>, "Arena") is the only daily, published in Los Angeles since 1908. ''[[Hairenik]]'' (<U+0540><U+0561><U+0575><U+0580><U+0565><U+0576><U+056B><U+0584>, "Fatherland") is published since 1899 in Boston.<ref name="Armenian Printing">{{cite web|last=Matiossian|first=Vartan|title=Teotig: The First Historian of Armenian Printing|url=http://www.armenianweekly.com/2012/08/31/teotig/|publisher=''[[The Armenian Weekly]]''|accessdate=26 November 2012|date=31 August 2012}}</ref> Both are affiliated with the [[Armenian Revolutionary Federation]]. Other notable weeklies include ''[[The Armenian Weekly]]'', ''[[Armenian Mirror-Spectator]]'', ''[[Nor Hayastan]]'' (<U+0546><U+0578><U+0580> <U+0540><U+0561><U+0575><U+0561><U+057D><U+057F><U+0561><U+0576>, "New Armenia"), ''[[The Armenian Reporter]]''.

Four Armenian television stations are located in the [[Southern California]], which has high concentration of Armenian speakers: [http://www.amga.tv/ AMGA] (Armenian Media Group of America), [http://armbesttv.com/ Armenian Best TV], [http://www.artn.tv/ ARTN] (Armenian-Russian Television Network), [http://usarmeniatv.com/ USArmenia TV]. Also, two TV stations are available only online: [http://www.horizonarmeniantv.com/ Horizon TV] and [http://www.hairenik.com/tv/ Hairenik TV].

There are bilingual radio stations that go on air either on Saturdays or Sundays for couple hours in [http://armenianradioboston.com/ Boston], [http://www.armenianradionj.com/ New Jersey], [http://www.armenianradiohour.com/ Providence], [http://www.hyeoozh.com/ Fresno] [http://www.armenianradioprogram.com/ Detroit]. Also, few online 24-hour radio stations operate nationwide: [http://www.yerevannights.com/ YerevanNights] and [http://www.armenianpulse.com/ Armenian Pulse] in Los Angeles, [http://bashde.org/ Bashde] and [http://www.hairenik.com/radio Hairenik Radio] in the Boston area.
<!--
===Traditions===
[[Armenian cuisine]] is widely popular among Armenian Americans. A number of restaurants function in the Los Angeles area. [[Zankou Chicken]], a family-owned chain of Armenian and Middle-Eastern fast casual restaurants within the Los Angeles area, is among the most famous Armenian restaurants. 

Tens of Armenian dance ensembles have been founded in the United States in the last decades.

wedding

[[Homenetmen]], an [[Armenian Revolutionary Federation]]-affiliated sports organization, is very active in the United States, also engaged in scouting. The Western US branch of Homenetmen holds the Navasartian Games in the Los Angeles area every summer since 1975. Today, it brings together more than 6,000 athletes from 300 teams, 2,000 scouts. More than 35,000 people come to watch the event.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Homenetmen Navasartian Games & Festival|url=http://www.navasartiangames.com/about-navasartian.php|publisher=Homenetmen Western USA|accessdate=30 May 2013}}</ref> 

