==Politics==
{{see also|Armenia <U+2013> United States relations|Diaspora politics in the United States}}
[[File:Armenian National Committee of America.JPG|thumb|200px|[[Armenian National Committee of America]] headquarters in Washington]]

===Early period===
The three major Armenian political parties of late 19th century and early 20th century <U+2014> Armenian Revolutionary Federation (Dashnaktsutyun), Social Democrat Hunchakian Party (Hunchak), [[Armenakan Party]] (later [[Ramgavar]]), were present in America not too long after their foundation.{{sfn|Ayvazyan|2003|p=42}} They established their own newspapers: ''[[Hairenik]]'' and ''[[Asbarez]]'' by [[Dashnaks]] and ''[[Baikar]]'' by Ramgavar's. After the Bolsheviks took over Armenia in 1920, Rmagavars and Hunchaks formed a coalition supporting Soviet Armenia, while the ARF, the ruling party of the Democratic Republic of Armenia from 1918 to 1920, remained anti-Soviet in diaspora.<ref name="Kouymjian"/> The [[1988 Spitak earthquake]] and the [[Karabakh movement]] brought the separate groups of the Armenian community together.<ref name="ny times 1988"/>

===Armenian lobby===
{{main|Armenian lobby in the United States}}
The Armenian American community has been described as the "most influential" Armenian community in the world, though smaller in size than the one in Russia.<ref name="Von Voss">{{cite book|last=Von Voss|first=Huberta|title=Portraits of hope: Armenians in the contemporary world|year=2007|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=New York|isbn=978-1-84545-257-5|page=11}}</ref> The [[Armenian American lobby]] is one of the most powerful ethnic lobbies in the US,<ref>[[Zbigniew Brzezinski|Brzezinski, Zbigniew]].  "A Dangerous Exemption." ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' 1 July 2006: 63.</ref> It is today considered to be the second most powerful ethnic lobby in America after the [[Jewish lobby]].<ref name="Papazian"/> The [[Armenian Assembly of America]] (AAA) and the [[Armenian National Committee of America]] (ANCA) have as their main lobbying agenda the pressing of Congress and the US President for an increase of economic aid to Armenia (already the second largest per capita after Israel) and the reduction of economic and military assistance to Turkey. The efforts also include reaffirmation of a genocide by Ottoman Turkey in 1915.<ref name="Cameron, Fraser pp.91">Cameron, Fraser ''United States foreign policy after the Cold War'' The Armenian-American'lobby, Routledge 2002 p.91</ref>

According to Shawn Dorman, the author of ''Inside a U.S. embassy'', the main goal of Armenian lobby is the "persuasion of US Congress to favor Armenian interests, especially to [[Recognition of the Armenian Genocide|recognize]] the Armenian Genocide." He then claims that "it had significant role in the United States providing financial support to Armenia. From 1992 to 2010 the US provided nearly $2 billion, the highest per capita amount for a post-Soviet state."<ref>{{cite book|last=Dorman|first=Shawn|title=Inside a U.S. embassy: diplomacy at work|publisher=Foreign Service Books|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-0-9649488-4-6|year=2011|page=10}}</ref> Fund for Armenian Relief is a humanitarian organization providing long-term programs focusing on human development. [[Armenia Fund]] raises millions of dollars every year for infrastructural development in Armenia and [[Nagorno-Karabakh]]. 

In 1992, Dr. [[Dickran Kouymjian]] of the [[California State University, Fresno]] stated in his essay:
{{cquote|All have refocused their efforts toward Armenia, providing financial and professional skill. The identification of Armenians with those in Erevan and Karabagh has been greatly facilitated by Armenia's membership in the United Nations and the regular reporting of its problems in the American press.. Diasporan history has been transformed by the Republic: nowhere is this more strongly felt than in America. The unifying force of the Genocide has been superseded by that of the Republic, while religious freedom in Armenia has revitalized the church in America and given it a mission. As the largest and most prosperous community in the world, as inheritors of a Protestant American work ethic, coupled with American self-righteousness, Armenian Americans feel they have a special role in the survival and success of the new state. They take pride in their support of Etchmiadzin, in the massive humanitarian aid given since the 1988 earthquake, in Armenians in high government positions, and particularly in the establishment of the American University of Armenia, the first major experiment in American higher education in the former Soviet Union. As English quickly becomes the second language of the new republic, Armenians in America feel closer to the homeland, suffering Armenia's tragedies and rejoicing in its successes. The Karabagh crisis, economic chaos, lack of basic amenities, and the threat of war fill all diasporan Armenians with an anxiety unknown before, because they know that their efforts may determine Armenia's fate.<ref name="Kouymjian"/>}}

[[File:Armenian Genocide Memorial, Montebello, California.jpg|left|thumb|150px|[[Montebello Genocide Memorial]]]]

===Armenian Genocide===
{{see also|Recognition of the Armenian Genocide|United States resolution on Armenian Genocide|Armenian Genocide Museum of America}}

The official recognition of the Armenian Genocide by the US federal government is seen one of the most vital steps in international and full recognition of the 1915<U+2013>1923 events. Many Armenians think that the US has the ability to force Turkey to recognize the past and pay Armenians and Armenia their reparations, that includes (for some) the return of the so-called [[Wilsonian Armenia]] to the Republic of Armenia. 

Several official US documents describe the events as "genocide" (1975,<ref name="Portraits of hope">{{cite book|last=Von Voss|first=Huberta|title=Portraits of hope: Armenians in the contemporary world|publisher=Bergahn Books|year=2007|page=36|isbn=978-1-84545-257-5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. House of Representatives Joint Resolution 148|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.157/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html|publisher=[[Armenian National Institute]]|accessdate=4 December 2012|date=9 April 1975}}</ref> 1984,<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. House of Representatives Joint Resolution 247|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.158/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html|publisher=[[Armenian National Institute]]|accessdate=4 December 2012|date=12 September 1984}}</ref> 1996<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. House of Representatives Resolution 3540|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.159/current_category.7/affirmation_detail.html|publisher=[[Armenian National Institute]]|accessdate=4 December 2012|date=11 June 1996}}</ref>); President [[Ronald Reagan]] also described the events as "genocide" in his speech on April 22, 1981.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armenian-genocide.org/Affirmation.63/current_category.4/affirmation_detail.html|title=Ronald Reagan, Proclamation, 22 April 1981|publisher=Armenian-genocide.org|date=22 April 1981|accessdate=4 December 2012}}</ref> On March 4, 2010, the U.S. House Committee on Foreign Affairs recognized the massacres of 1915 as "genocide."<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. House panel approves Armenia genocide resolution|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-03/05/c_13197636.htm|accessdate=15 December 2012|date=5 March 2010|newspaper=[[Xinhua]]}}</ref> Also, 43 of the 50 US states have made individual proclamations recognizing the events of 1915 to 1923 as genocide.<ref>{{cite web|title=Provincial governments|url=http://www.genocide-museum.am/eng/provincial_governments.php|publisher=Armenian Genocide Museum-Institute|accessdate=13 January 2013}}</ref> 

Armenian Americans gather in multiple towns and cities every year on April 24 for the recognition of the Armenian Genocide. The largest of such gatherings occurs in the Los Angeles area. The [[Armenian National Institute]] lists 30 Armenian Genocide memorials in the US.<ref>{{cite news|title=ANI expands Armenian Genocide memorials data base|url=http://panarmenian.net/m/eng/news/121825|accessdate=13 January 2013|date=6 September 2012|agency=[[PanARMENIAN.Net]]}}</ref>  The oldest one is [[Montebello Genocide Memorial]], which was completed in 1965. [[Khachkar]]s across America were erected in honor of the 1.5 million victims of the Genocide. Recently, the [[Armenian Heritage Park (Boston)|Armenian Heritage Park]] was opened in Boston, MA.
{{clear}}

== Notable Armenian Americans==
{{double image|right|Pamboukjian in Aleppo.jpg|105|Armenchik.jpg|124|[[Harout Pamboukjian]] and [[Armenchik]] are representatives of two generations of Armenian singers in America.}}
{{main|List of Armenian Americans}}
Armenians in the US have attained success and prominence in diverse areas, including business, entertainment, sciences, sports and literature.

===Arts and entertainment ===
[[File:SoaD.jpg|left|thumb|[[System of a Down]] is composed of four Armenians]]
[[File:William Saroyan 1970s.jpg|thumb|150px|[[William Saroyan]] was a major Armenian American figure throughout the 20th century]]
;Music
Entertainment has been, perhaps, the most successful area for Armenian Americans. Numerous Armenian musicians have been successful in American pop culture. Los Angeles is considered one of the main centers of Armenian music production of the last two decades.

Armenian-born singers that have lived or live in the US include rock singer [[Arthur Meschian]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://www.arthurmeschian.com/lang/en/biography.php|publisher=Arthur Meschian {{!}} Official Website|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> folk singers [[Harout Pamboukjian]]<ref>{{cite web|title=About Harout|url=http://www.haroutpamboukjian.com/biography|publisher=Harout Pamboukjian Website|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> and [[Flora Martirosian]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://floramartirosian.com/web/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=8&Itemid=25&lang=en|publisher=Flora Martirosian Website|accessdate=19 December 2012}}</ref> and pop singer [[Armenchik]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography|url=http://armenmusic.com/news/?page_id=2|publisher=Armenchik Official Website|accessdate=18 December 2012}}</ref> [[Arto Tun<U+00E7>boyac<U+0131>yan]], an avant-garde singer from Istanbul, also lived in America for many years. One of the most discussed American singers, [[Cher]] (born Cherilyn Sarkisian), is Armenian from paternal side.<ref>{{cite book|last=Barkan|first=Elliott Robert|title=Making it in America: a sourcebook on eminent ethnic Americans|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=978-1-57607-098-7|page=333}}</ref> The metal band [[System of a Down]] is composed of four Armenian members.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hovanissian|first=Richard|title=The Armenian genocide: cultural and ethical legacies|year=2007|publisher=Transaction Publishers|location=New Brunswick, New Jersey|isbn=978-1-4128-0619-0|page=221}}</ref> 

;Literature
Armenian American literature constitutes a diverse body of literature that incorporates American writers of Armenian ancestry. Encompassing a cross section of literary genres and forms, Armenian American writers often incorporate some common themes (e.g., the Armenian Genocide) while maintaining very personal literary styles. The New York-based ''[[Ararat Quarterly]]'', published since 1959, has been a major venue for Armenian American writing. ''Ararat'' is published in English by the [[AGBU]] and also includes works by Armenian writers around the world in translation. First-generation Armenian American writers include William Saroyan, [[Leon Surmelian]], [[A. I. Bezzerides]], [[Michael Arlen]],   [[Marjorie Housepian Dobkin]] and others. Second generation Armenian American writers include [[Peter Balakian]], [[Nancy Kricorian]], [[Carol Edgarian]], [[Michael J. Arlen]], [[Arthur Nersesian]], [[Micheline Aharonian Marcom]], [[Hrag Vartanian]], [[Chris Bohjalian]] and others.<ref>Forgotten Bread: First-Generation Armenian American Writers, ed. David Kherdian (Heyday, 2007)</ref>

;Visual arts
Sculptor [[Haig Patigian]], painters [[Hovsep Pushman]] and, most notably, [[Arshile Gorky]] are the most famous American artists of Armenian origin.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=192}} [[Rouben Mamoulian]], a film and theater director also known as co-producer of the first feature film (''[[Becky Sharp]]'', 1935) to use the three-strip Technicolor process.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=415}} [[Ross Bagdasarian, Sr.]], William Saroyan's cousin, created the [[Alvin and the Chipmunks]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Talevski|first=Nick|title=Knocking on heavens's door: rock obituaries|year=2006|publisher=Omnibus Press|location=London|isbn=978-1-84609-091-2|page=582}}</ref>

[[File:George Deukmejian Official Portrait crop.jpg|thumb|left|210px|[[George Deukmejian]] was the [[Governor of California]] from 1983 to 1991]]
=== Politicians ===
{{main|List of American politicians of Armenian descent}}

A number of Armenians have entered into politics. The first Armenian to hold a high position office was Republican [[Steven Derounian]], a Bulgarian-born Armenian, represented New York from 1953 to 1965 in the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=255}} [[George Deukmejian]] became the [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] governor of California in 1983 and left the office in 1991. Previously he had served as State Assemblyman (1963<U+2013>1967), State Senator (1967<U+2013>1979) and [[California Attorney General]] (1979<U+2013>1983).{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=254}} A number of Armenian American had been elected to state legislatures, especially in California. In Massachusetts, [[George Keverian]] wasn't only elected to the [[Massachusetts House of Representatives|State House]], but also became its speaker from 1985 to 1991.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=255}} 

[[Paul Robert Ignatius]] served as the [[US Secretary of the Navy]] from 1967 to 1969 in the Lyndon Johnson's administration.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=281}} [[Ken Khachigian]] was the chief speechwriter for President Ronald Reagan. He is also known for Reagan's characterization of 1915 events as "genocide" in 1981.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bobelian|first=Michael|title=Children of Armenia: a forgotten genocide and the century-long struggle for justice|year=2009|publisher=Simon & Schuster|location=New York|isbn=978-1-4165-5725-8|page=169}}</ref> Diplomat [[Edward Djerejian]] was the US ambassador in Syria then Israel in the 1990s.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=281}} [[Harry Tutunjian]] was the [[Republican party (United States)|Republican]] mayor of Troy, New York from 2003 to 2012. [[Joe Simitian]] had been a California State Senator since 2004,{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=255}} while [[Paul Krekorian]] was elected to the Los Angeles City Council in 2010 from [[Los Angeles City Council District 2|District 2]], where the Armenian population of Los Angeles is concentrated. Currently, two congresswoman of Armenian ancestry, [[Anna Eshoo]] and [[Jackie Speier]], are in the office, both Democrats from California.{{sfn|Adalian|2010|p=255}}

A small number of Armenian Americans moved to Armenia in early 1990s, some becoming notable in their ancestral homeland. [[Raffi Hovannisian]], a Fresno-born third-generation Armenian American lawyer, moved to Armenia in 1991 and soon was appointed the first Foreign Minister of Armenia, where he remained until 1992. Today, Hovannisian is major opposition figure in Armenia and the leader of [[Heritage (Armenia)|Heritage]] party. Sebouh (Steve) Tashjian, a California Armenian originally from Jerusalem, served as Minister of Energy, while Lebanese-born Gerard (Jirair) Libaridian, a Boston-based historian, was President [[Levon Ter-Petrosyan]]'s advisor.<ref>{{cite book|last=Herzig|first=Edmund|title=The Armenians: past and present in the making of national identity|year=2005|publisher=RoutledgeCurzon|location=London|isbn=978-0-7007-0639-6|pages=231<U+2013>232|coauthors=Kurkchiyan, Marina}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Krikorian|first=Robert O.|title=Armenia: at the crossroads|year=1999|publisher=Taylor & Francis|location=Amsterdam|isbn=978-90-5702-345-3|pages=38<U+2013>39|coauthors=Masih, Joseph R.}}</ref> Another native of California, [[Monte Melkonian]], was a prominent leader of Armenian forces during the Nagorno-Karabakh War. He was posthumously awarded with [[National Hero of Armenia]] title.<ref>{{cite book|last=von Voss|first=Huberta|title=Portraits of hope: Armenians in the contemporary world|year=2007|publisher=Berghahn Books|location=New York|isbn=978-1-84545-257-5|page=237}}</ref> 
{{clear}}
===Military ===
Several major figures of the [[Armenian national liberation movement]] of early 20th century lived and/or died in the US. Among them were [[Andranik Ozanian]], a military commander who is considered an national hero among Armenians, lived in Fresno, California since 1922 and died in California in 1927.<ref>{{cite book|last=Avakian|first=Arra S.|title=Armenia: a Journey Through History|year=1998|publisher=Electric Press|isbn=978-0-916919-20-7|pages=311<U+2013>314}}</ref> Another notable military commander, [[Garegin Nzhdeh]], lived in Boston, Massachusetts from 1933 to 1937, where he founded the [[Armenian Youth Federation]]. [[Drastamat Kanayan]] (Dro), the Defense Minister of Armenia from 1918 to 1919, lived in America after the World War II and was shortly arrested for collaborating with the Nazis. His funeral ceremony was held in [[Trinity Church (Boston)|Trinity Church in the City of Boston]] in 1956. [[Shahan Natalie]], a Dashnak activist, organized the [[Operation Nemesis]] in early 1920s, during which numerous Armenian Genocide perpetrators were murdered. From 1910 to 1912 he studied at the [[Boston University]] and died in Watertown, Massachusetts in 1983.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shahan Natalie: a biography|url=http://www.snff.org/about/shahan-natalie/|publisher=Shahan Natalie Family Foundation, Inc.|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref>

During World War II, about 18,500 Armenians served in the [[armed forces of the United States]].<ref>Tashjian, James H. (1952) ''The Armenian American in World War II''. Boston: Harenik Association</ref> A number of them were decorated for their service, including Col. [[Ernest Dervishian]], a native of [[Virginia]], who was awarded the [[Congressional Medal of Honor]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Ernest Herbert Dervishian|url=http://militarytimes.com/citations-medals-awards/recipient.php?recipientid=825|publisher=Military Times Hall Of Valor|accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref> US Marine [[Harry Kizirian]] is considered the most decorated soldier of the state of Rhode Island.<ref>{{cite news|title=Much-beloved Rhode Islander regarded as 'national treasure' <U+2013> Harry Kizirian, postmaster, war hero, dies|accessdate=29 April 2013|newspaper=[[The Providence Journal]]|date=15 September 2002|page=C-01|quote=Kizirian, a former Marine widely acclaimed as the most decorated soldier from Rhode Island in World War II, served on numerous boards of directors, was honored by dozens of local organizations and was a member of the Rhode Island Hall of Fame. Regarded as a "national treasure," Kizirian received an honorary doctor of public service degree from Rhode Island College in 1992.}}</ref> Another Marine Captain, [[Victor Maghakian]] is considered one of the most decorated American soldiers of the war.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bulbulian|first=Berge|title=The Fresno Armenians: History of a Diaspora Community|year=2000|publisher=California State University Press|location=Fresno|isbn=0912201355|page=193|quote=He was one of the most decorated military men in World War II having won the Navy Cross, Silver Star with Gold Star, Bronze Star, the Purple Heart and many other medals.}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Tashjian|first=James H.|title='Transport' Maghakian|journal=Armenian Review|year=1952|volume=5|page=43|quote=He fought from the Makin Raid through Tinian in the Pacific, came out of it all, on the testimony of the Department of the Navy, "one of the highest decorated" Marines of World War II.}}</ref>

[[File:ZildjianCustomRide.jpg|thumb|220px|The [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Company]] is the largest cymbal manufacturer in the world.<ref>{{cite book|title=Management|year=2011|publisher=South-Western Cengage|location=Mason, OH|isbn=9781111221362|page=35|author=Robert Kreitner, Carlene M. Cassidy|edition=12th ed.|quote=Company, based in Norwell, Massachusetts, is the largest cymbal maker in the world and the oldest continuously family-run business in the United States.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Lamb|first=Charles W.|title=The Subject is Marketing|year=2002|publisher=Nelson Thomson Learning|location=Scarborough, Ont.|isbn=9780176169558|page=26|edition=2nd Canadian ed.|quote=Avedis Zildjian of Norwell, Massachusetts, can trace its history back to 1623 in Constantinople. It is the world's largest maker of cymbals for drummers and musicians.}}</ref><ref>''[[Newsweek]]'', Volume 71, Issues 1-9, 1968, p. 71 "As the only producer of cymbals in the U.S., the Zildjian company dominates a world market rapidly expanding with the proliferation of per- cussionary rock 'n' roll bands."</ref><ref>''[[The Music Trades (magazine)|The Music Trades]]'', Volume 135, Issues 1-6, p. 90 "Maintaining its position as the world's largest cymbal producer, the Avedis Zildjian Company has announced an exciting joint venture with Barcus-Berry, Inc."</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Robert Zildjian Dead: Founder Of Sabian Cymbal Company Dies At 89|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/29/robert-zildjian-dead-sabian-cymbals-obituary_n_2976363.html|accessdate=25 May 2013|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=29 March 2013|quote=zildjian cymbal largest producer}}</ref>]]

===Miscellaneous===
Other notable Armenian Americans include [[Jack Kevorkian]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Nicol|first=Neal|title=Between the dying and the dead: Dr. Jack Kevorkian's life and the battle to legalize euthanasia|year=2006|publisher=Univ. of Wisconsin Press|location=Madison, Wisconsin|isbn=978-0-299-21710-5|coauthors=Wylie, Harry|page=27}}</ref> a [[pathologist]] and [[euthanasia]] activist who was commonly referred to as "Dr. Death", and astronaut [[James P. Bagian]], who became the first Armenian to travel into space in 1989.<ref>{{cite book|last=Gore|first=Patrick Wilson|title='Tis some poor fellow's skull: post-Soviet warfare in the southern Caucasus|year=2008|publisher=iUniverse|location=New York|isbn=978-0-595-48679-3|page=21}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Akopian|first=Aram|title=Armenians and the world: yesterday and today|year=2001|publisher=Noyan Tapan|location=Yerevan|isbn=978-99930-51-29-9|page=61}}</ref> It is claimed that he took the [[Armenian tricolor]] to space with him.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Washington Journalism Review: WJR|year=1989|volume= 11|publisher=Washington Communications Corporation}}</ref> 

Famous figures in national sports include tennis player, former no. 1 [[Andre Agassi]],<ref>{{cite book|title=The Agassi story|year=2004|publisher=ECW Press|location=Toronto|isbn=978-1-55022-656-0|author=Mike Agassi, Dominic Cobello|page=12}}</ref> chess players [[Tatev Abrahamyan]] and [[Varuzhan Akobian]]. [[Hal Haig Prieste]], who won a bronze medal diving in [[1920 Summer Olympics|1920 Antwerp Games]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Lutz|first=Stuart|title=The Last Leaf: Voices of History's Last-Known Survivors|year=2010|publisher=Prometheus Books|isbn=978-1-61614-310-7|page=341}}</ref> soccer player [[Alecko Eskandarian]], wrestler [[Frankie Kazarian]], and MLB pitcher [[Steve Bedrosian]]. [[Adam Krikorian]] is the current [[US women's national water polo team]] head coach. The team won 2010 World Cup and 2012 Olympics under his coaching. [[Zach Bogosian]] is the first NHL player of Armenian descent. Current [[MLB Network]] and [[FOX Sports]] broadcaster [[Matt Vasgersian]] is also of Armenian heritage.

Some notable Armenian Americans in business include Turkish-born founder of [[Masco]] [[Alex Manoogian]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Barkan|first=Elliott Robert|title=Making it in America: a sourcebook on eminent ethnic Americans|year=2001|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, California|isbn=978-1-57607-098-7|pages=217<U+2013>218}}</ref> the [[Mugar family]] (owner of [[Star Market]] chain of supermarkets in New England),<ref>{{cite book|last=Gabaccia|first=Donna|title=We are what we eat: ethnic food and the making of Americans|year=2000|publisher=Harvard Univ. Press|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|isbn=978-0-674-00190-9|page=76}}</ref> [[Kevork Hovnanian]], founder of [[Hovnanian Enterprises]], Avedis Zildjian, the founder of [[Avedis Zildjian Company|Zildjian Company]] (world's largest cymbal manufacturer) and [[Gerard Cafesjian]]. 95-year-old Armenian American businessman [[Kirk Kerkorian]], known as "the father of the megaresort",<ref name="Simich">{{cite book|last=Simich|first=Jerry L.|title=More peoples of Las Vegas: one city, many faces|year=2010|publisher=University of Nevada Press|isbn=978-0-87417-817-3|coauthors=Wright, Thomas C.|page=143}}</ref> is claimed to be the richest man in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|last=Goldberg|first=Ryan|title=Rags to Riches CEOs: Kirk Kerkorian|url=http://www.minyanville.com/businessmarkets/articles/ceo-mgm-mirage-vegas-casinos-forbes/11/18/2009/id/25331|accessdate=1 January 2013|date=18 November 2009|newspaper=[[Minyanville]]}}</ref> Born to Armenian parents in Fresno, Kerkorian had provided over $1 billion for charity in Armenia through his Lincy Foundation.<ref name="Simich"/> It was established in 1989 and was particularly focused on helping to rebuilt northern Armenia after the 1988 Spitak earthquake.<ref>{{cite book|title=American foundations: roles and contributions|year=2010|publisher=Brookings Institution Press|location=Washington, D.C.|isbn=978-0-8157-0339-6|author=Dr Helmut K Anheier, David C. Hammack|page=241}}</ref> The foundation was dissolved in 2011, after 22-year activities.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kirk Kerkorian is not offended by Armenia|url=http://armeniadiaspora.com/news/5009-kirk-kerkorian-is-not-offended-by-armenia-.html|accessdate=1 January 2013|date=14 September 2011|agency=''ArmeniaDiaspora.com''}}</ref> 

[[Aram Chobanian]] served as President of Boston University from 2003 to 2005. Dr. [[Richard Hovannisian]], father of Armenian-based politician Raffi Hovannisian, is a renowned historian at the University of California, Los Angeles.

